docBody.p:
Poor Lady Ashburton, we hear yesterday with real grief, has had a tumble (mule-carriage overset) in the Vevay mountns;
The Vevey mountains in Switzerland; see TC to Lady A., 18 Aug.
 whh has thrown out her shoulder joint, a thing of probably ill consequence, apart from the pain of it. And poor Dr Barnes junr (a very nice yg man) has suddenly died;
The Times, 28 Sept., announced the death: “On the 26th inst., at Hotel de Lille and D’Albion, Paris, Herbert Sedgwick, the younger and dearly-loved son of Alfred Brooke Barnes, Esq., of Chelsea, aged 29.” Frances Blunt brought JWC the news; see Reginald Blunt, Memoirs of Gerald Blunt of Chelsea (1911) 90.
 —his poor old Father, now quite gone in the head, can hardly be made to understand it; weeps copiously, then after a time forgets. Telle est la vie [Such is life]. Let us love one another all: oh dear!—
T.C.

div3.sourceNote:
TC-JMC, [Sept. 1865?]. Pbd: Maggs Bros. catalog inc; the note was inserted into a copy of The French Revolution (1837). Julia Margaret Cameron (1815–79; 
                ODNB
              ), photographer. The letter was written after Cameron took up photography (1863) and before JWC died (21 April 1866). Conjecturally dated Sept. 1865 after the Carlyles had a spate of photographs taken by John Watkins and Elliott & Fry, April 1865 (
              TC to JOWA, 21 April 1865
            ; JWC to JOWA, [25 April 1865]; 
            JWC to MCA, [ca. 25 April 1865]; and vol. 42), and when they were both back in Chelsea after their respective summer travels. It precedes 
              TC to AWH, [late Sept. 1865]. [This letter, pbd. at CL 44:236, is now placed at its proper chronological location. In order to preserve the order established by the editors, it has been assigned a document date of 30 September 1865.]
